","header":"He taught anatomy at Harvard for decades","body":"Charles Sedgwick Minot graduated from MIT in 1872, studied in Leipzig, Paris, and Würzburg, and taught comparative anatomy at Harvard Medical School from 1880 until his death. He pioneered the study of cellular aging and assembled one of the era's great embryological collections."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"He helped found a psychical research society","body":"A rigorous empiricist, Minot was a founding member of the American Society for Psychical Research but resigned over its unscientific drift. He publicly attacked the claims of Theosophy and so-called esoteric Buddhism."},{"category":"science","header":"He asked why living things must age","body":"Minot turned the microscope on mortality itself, studying how cells slow and decline with age. His 1908 book, The Problem of Age, Growth, and Death, made him a pioneer of the science of senescence.","number":3},{"category":"legacy","header":"Yale and Oxford honored the Roxbury anatomist","body":"Honorary degrees came from Yale, Toronto, St. Andrews, and Oxford, and he presided over the American Association for the Advancement of Science. From 1912 he taught as Harvard's exchange professor in Berlin and Jena.","number":4}],"slug":"charles-minot-1852"},"HD2336":{"id":"HD2336","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00741","mother_id":"HD2329"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1856,"month":8,"city":"West Roxbury","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1910,"month":5,"city":"Dover","state":"Massachusetts"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00742","children_ids":["HD2337","HD2360"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1885,"date_month":1,"date_day":30}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{